[1
[State surveillance programs have run down. New York State is the only
state to release a new update, reporting one new human case. All other
reports and test results remain as posted in West Nile virus surveillance -
USA (47). The United States Department of Agriculture site which records
the overall totals has not been up-dated beyond 31 Oct 2000 as yet and
remains as posted in West Nile virus surveillance - USA (46). The November
24, 2000 edition of the Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report contains an
Update of West Nile Virus Activity for the Eastern United States, 2000
<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm4946a2.htm>. The Update
presents surveillance data reported to CDC from 1 Jan 2000 through 15 Nov
2000. The analysis of mosquito pools in this report notes that several
species formerly classified in the genus _Aedes_ have been transferred to
the genus _Ochlerotatus_. - Mod.CP
New York State
--------------
Date: 1 Dec 2000
Source: New York State Department of Health, West Nile virus Update [edited
<http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/update/today.htm>

This week (25 Nov 2000 - 1 Dec 2000), the New York State Health
Department's Wadsworth Center laboratories reported one new human West Nile
Virus case in Manhattan. [No other details are given. - Mod.CP
Note that the text report and the New York State summary map
<http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/update/today.pdf> report
West Nile virus positive results. Encephalitis or severe neurologic
symptoms were not present in all of the human, bird, and mammal positive
"cases". A number of the birds and mammals had no clinical signs of West
Nile virus infection at all; they were asymptomatic surveillance specimens.
The total number of West Nile virus positive specimens from New York State
for this year is 1271 dead birds, 357 mosquito pools, 2 sentinel chickens,
8 live wild birds, 14 bats, 24 horses, 2 cats, 2 raccoons, 3 domestic
rabbits, 3 squirrels, one chipmunk, and 14 human cases.
