[2
Date: 26 Nov 2000 11:45:52 -0500
From: Eleanor Kellon <kell@epix.net>

West Nile virus infection of horses
-----------------------------------
I would like to point out that New York State's latest surveillance
numbers, cited in WNV surveillance - USA (49), bring the total of equine
West Nile virus confirmations to 64 for the year; horses by far being the
most frequently affected mammal. Interesting to note that cases did not
appear as early as might have been expected by the early viral activity.
Also positive test results for the horses continue to mount this year even
while the bird numbers are dropping precipitously. Does this implicate
different mosquito vectors for horses than humans? Longer incubation? Any
other ideas as to the reasons for this pattern?
--
Eleanor Kellon, VMD
Technical/Veterinary Editor
Horse Journal
<kell@epix.net>
[Dr. Kellon raises some interesting questions. West Nile virus infection
has been confirmed in 65 horses with neurologic disease from 26 Counties in
7 States, whereas 18 (now 19) human cases with severe neurologic disease
were recorded in the States of New Jersey and New York, plus one mildly
symptomatic case in Connecticut. Data presented graphically in the MMWR
Report of 24 Nov 2000 show that the incidence of disease in horses peaked
and persisted after the human illnesses. The report concludes that horses
may not be a sensitive sentinel for the prediction of human illness. - Mod.CP
